description: Aerosmith AeroHistoy: Walk This Way  On this day back in 1975 Aerosmith releases the single Walk This Way.  Written by Steven Tyler and Joe Perry, the song was originally released as the second single from the 1975 album Toys in the Attic. It peaked at number 10 on the Billboard Hot 100 in early 1977, part of a string of successful hit singles for the band in the 1970s. In addition to being one of the songs that helped break Aerosmith into the mainstream in the 1970s, it also helped revitalize their career in the 1980s when it was covered by rappers Run‚ÄìD.M.C. on their 1986 album Raising Hell. This cover was a touchstone for the new musical subgenre of rap rock, or the melding of rock and hip hop. It became an international hit and won both groups a Soul Train Music Award for Best Rap ‚Äì Single in 1987.

Monday Motivation from Your Realtor Lisa Potter

Give yourself this Gift: Take 3 minutes of your day to read these Powerful Words from Richard Branson...    "Dear Stranger,  You don‚Äôt know me but I hear you are going through a tough time, and I would like to help you. I want to be open and honest with you, and let you know that happiness isn‚Äôt something just afforded to a special few. It can be yours, if you take the time to let it grow.  It‚Äôs OK to ...  be stressed, scared and sad, I certainly have been throughout my 66 years. I‚Äôve confronted my biggest fears time and time again. I‚Äôve cheated death on many adventures, seen loved ones pass away, failed in business, minced my words in front of tough audiences, and had my heart broken.  I know I‚Äôm fortunate to live an extraordinary life, and that most people would assume my business success, and the wealth that comes with it, have brought me happiness. But they haven‚Äôt; in fact it‚Äôs the reverse. I am successful, wealthy and connected because I am happy.  So many people get caught up in doing what they think will make them happy but, in my opinion, this is where they fail. Happiness is not about doing, it‚Äôs about being. In order to be happy, you need to think consciously about it. Don‚Äôt forget the to-do list, but remember to write a to-be list too.  Kids are often asked: ‚ÄòWhat do you want to be when you grow up?‚Äô The world expects grandiose aspirations: ‚ÄòI want to be a writer, a doctor, the prime minister.‚Äô They‚Äôre told: go to school, go to college, get a job, get married, and then you‚Äôll be happy. But that‚Äôs all about doing, not being ‚Äì and while doing will bring you moments of joy, it won‚Äôt necessarily reward you with lasting happiness.  Stop and breathe. Be healthy. Be around your friends and family. Be there for someone, and let someone be there for you. Be bold. Just be for a minute.  If you allow yourself to be in the moment, and appreciate the moment, happiness will follow. I speak from experience. We‚Äôve built a business empire, joined conversations about the future of our planet, attended many memorable parties and met many unforgettable people. And while these things have brought me great joy, it‚Äôs the moments that I stopped just to be, rather than do, that have given me true happiness. Why? Because allowing yourself just to be, puts things into perspective. Try it. Be still. Be present.  For me, it‚Äôs watching the flamingos fly across Necker Island at dusk. It‚Äôs holding my new grandchild's tiny hands. It‚Äôs looking up at the stars and dreaming of seeing them up close one day. It‚Äôs listening to my family‚Äôs dinner-time debates. It‚Äôs the smile on a stranger‚Äôs face, the smell of rain, the ripple of a wave, the wind across the sand. It‚Äôs the first snow fall of winter, and the last storm of summer. It‚Äôs sunrise and sunset.  There‚Äôs a reason we‚Äôre called human beings and not human doings. As human beings we have the ability to think, move and communicate in a heightened way. We can cooperate, understand, reconcile and love, that‚Äôs what sets us apart from most other species.  Don‚Äôt waste your human talents by stressing about nominal things, or that which you cannot change. If you take the time simply to be and appreciate the fruits of life, your stresses will begin to dissolve, and you will be happier.  But don‚Äôt just seek happiness when you‚Äôre down. Happiness shouldn‚Äôt be a goal, it should be a habit. Take the focus off doing, and start being every day. Be loving, be grateful, be helpful, and be a spectator to your own thoughts.  Allow yourself to be in the moment, and appreciate the moment. Take the focus off everything you think you need to do, and start being ‚Äì I promise you, happiness will follow.  Happy regards,  Richard Branson"   See More

2 cans left. These are the last two cans of wet kitten food in our entire foster department, and we desperately need more. We currently have over 200 underage kittens in foster homes right now and we have taken in more kittens to date than we did last year, when we took in over 1300 kittens. Wet kitten food is different than wet adult cat food and is vital in transitioning a kitten to solid food f ... rom its mother‚Äôs milk. That transition is a very crucial part of a kitten‚Äôs survival, and if they are able to transition away from their mother‚Äôs milk and to solid foods when they are old enough, their chance of survival significantly increases. The ability to eat on their own is one of the biggest factors for our ability to take in the majority of our kittens (due to a lack of bottle baby fosters, which every rescue struggles with), and this is the food necessary to feed them.  If you have the ability to donate some, we would greatly appreciate it. We prefer Pro Plan kitten wet food and Royal Canin Kitten wet food, which can be found online below or at your local Petsmart or Petco. We, and our underage kittens, thank you for anything you can provide. description: Mary Hanson  added  36 new photos  ‚Äî with  Lisa Potter  and  16 others . Just returned from the family reunion in Maine. Wow. It was wonderful. We all now feel so renewed by lots of unconditional love. We kayaked, hiked, played games by the fire, tubed behind the speed boat (THANK YOU, JESS!!), swam, dove off the floating docks, ate tons of lobster and other shell fish, messed around on the beach on the island, took evening cruises while the sun set, had hatchet throwing contests, rented horses to ride and ALL got addicted to the sound of the loons!! We also sang together in the evening. Luckily, after the first night, neighbors told us they liked it and wanted us to do more!  :-)  We had a some falls, injuries and getting sick, but everyone shared medicine, bandages, massages, advice and trips to town to get needed stuff, so we all survived. The age range ran from 18 months to 83 years and lots in between. The airlines cooperated beautifully for us to all GET there, but threw us some curves trying to get home. But we all reconnected and our hearts are now stronger for being together, and we feel better prepared to face the world in our separate locations. I pray for everyone in this family (almost) every day. So worth it. ps Deeply, DEEPLY!!! missed the family members  who could not be there... especially my own two daughters!!  <3   <3 Karly Ana Gloria Nathan
